In LaTeX, you can generate a table of contents automatically using the `toc` package and the `chapter` and `section` commands. Here's an example document that demonstrates how to create a table of contents:
```sql
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{toc}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\chapter{Introduction}

\section{Background}

\section{Problem Statement}

\section{Methodology}

\section{Results}

\section{Discussion}

\section{Conclusion}

\end{document}
```
In this example, we start with a basic LaTeX document and include the `toc` package. We then use the `\tableofcontents` command to generate the table of contents.

The table of contents is automatically generated based on the chapter and section headings in the document. Each chapter and section is displayed as a separate entry in the table of contents, along with the page number where it begins.

To use the `toc` package, you need to include the following command in your document preamble:
```python
\usepackage{toc}
```
This command tells LaTeX to use the `toc` package to generate the table of contents.

You can also customize the appearance of the table of contents using various options provided by the `toc` package. For example, you can change the font size, style, or color of the entries, or add custom labels or page numbers.

Here's an example of how to customize the table of contents using the `tocstyle` package:
```sql
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{toc}
\usepackage{tocstyle}

\setcounter{tocdepth}{3} % Set the toc depth to 3 levels
\renewcommand\printtoc[1]{\tableofcontents} % Redefine printtoc to display the table of contents
\tocstyle
\renewcommand{\tocnumfont}{\tiny} % Set the font size for the table of contents numbers
\renewcommand{\tocnumlabel}{\textbf{\thecontentslabel}} % Set the font style and label for the table of contents numbers
\renewcommand{\tocpagefont}{\small} % Set the font size for the table of contents page numbers

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\chapter{Introduction}

\section{Background}

\section{Problem Statement}

\section{Methodology}

\section{Results}

\section{Discussion}

\section{Conclusion}

\end{document}
```
In this example, we use the `tocstyle` package to customize the appearance of the table of contents. We set the `tocdepth` option to 3 levels (i.e., we want to include headings up to and including section 3), and we redefine the `printtoc` command to display the table of contents.

We also use several other `tocstyle` options to customize the font sizes and styles for the table of contents entries. For example, we use `\tocnumfont` to set the font size for the numbers in the table of contents, and we use `\tocnumlabel` to set the font style and label for the numbers. We also use `\tocpagefont` to set the font size for the page numbers in the table of contents.

By using the `toc` and `tocstyle` packages, you can easily generate a professional-looking table of contents for your LaTeX document.

